\section{Rendering the tutorial list}

The same command serves two audiences.  At an interactive terminal, Rich
can align the columns without the box-drawing borders that would add visual
noise to a short list.  In pipelines, though, plain tab-separated rows are
easier to parse, so the non-TTY form omits headers and writes one row per
tutorial.

<<functions>>=
def render_tutorial_list(
    console: Console,
    tutorials: tuple[tuple["Tutorial", ProgressState], ...],
) -> None:
    """Render the tutorial list for terminals and scripts."""

    if console.is_terminal:
        table = Table(box=None)
        table.add_column("Tutorial", style="bold")
        table.add_column("Progress", no_wrap=True)
        table.add_column("Summary")
        for tutorial, progress in tutorials:
            table.add_row(
                tutorial.id,
                format_progress_status(progress),
                tutorial.summary,
            )
        console.print(table)
        return

    writer = csv.writer(
        console.file,
        dialect="excel-tab",
        lineterminator="\n",
    )
    for tutorial, progress in tutorials:
        writer.writerow(
            (
                tutorial.id,
                format_progress_status(progress),
                tutorial.summary,
            )
        )
@

