\section{Building the Typer application}

The standalone CLI and Typer embedding both rely on the same shared command
set.  Using a factory rather than a single global app keeps the namespace
and state-root configuration overridable for tests and host applications.

We still make help the default action when no subcommand is given.  That is
friendlier for the standalone binary, and it also helps embedded hosts
because [[host tutorial]] should explain itself instead of failing with a
missing-command error.

Typer's built-in [[no_args_is_help]] prints the right help text, but in the
current Typer/Click combination it still exits with the usual
missing-command status.  We therefore make the group invokable without a
subcommand and emit the help text ourselves when nothing was selected.

<<functions>>=
def create_app(
    *,
    namespace: str = "tutorial",
    state_root: str | Path | None = None,
    tutorial_paths: tuple[str | Path, ...] = (),
    tutorial_path_provider: Callable[[], tuple[str | Path, ...]] | None = None,
    shell_runner: Callable[..., object] = run_interactive_shell,
    editor_runner: Callable[..., object] = run_editor,
    question_runner: Callable[..., ShellResult] | None = None,
    allow_shell: bool = False,
) -> typer.Typer:
    """Create a Typer application for tutorials."""

    <<create Typer application shell>>
    <<register help callback>>
    <<define shared tutorial path resolution>>
    <<define shared runner factory>>
    <<define completion callbacks>>
    <<register list command>>
    <<register run command>>
    <<register review command>>

    return application
@

The factory starts by creating the Typer shell once.  Every later section adds
one concern to that shell: first the group callback, then shared helpers, and
finally the user-facing commands.

<<create Typer application shell>>=
application = typer.Typer(
    help="Run interactive command-line tutorials.",
    invoke_without_command=True,
)
@

The help callback belongs close to the application shell because it changes the
group's default behaviour, not one specific command.

<<register help callback>>=
@application.callback(invoke_without_command=True)
def app_callback(ctx: typer.Context) -> None:
    """Show help when the tutorial group is invoked without a command."""

    if ctx.invoked_subcommand is None:
        typer.echo(ctx.get_help())
        raise typer.Exit(code=0)
@

Each command resolves its own extra tutorial paths, but the configured base
paths come from one place.  Keeping that logic in one closure lets tests and
embedding hosts override the source without repeating the fallback rule.

<<define shared tutorial path resolution>>=
def configured_tutorial_paths() -> tuple[str | Path, ...]:
    if tutorial_path_provider is not None:
        return tuple(tutorial_path_provider())
    return tuple(tutorial_paths)
@

Every command eventually needs the same runner wiring: combine tutorial paths,
optionally require at least one path, and thread through the chosen backends.
The local closure adapts the shared [[build_command_runner()]] helper to the
current app factory so the Typer sections below can talk about command-specific
behaviour rather than replaying the runner setup.

<<define shared runner factory>>=
def runner(
    *,
    command_tutorial_paths: tuple[str | Path, ...] = (),
    command_allow_shell: bool = False,
    require_paths: bool = False,
    question_runner_override: Callable[..., ShellResult] | None = None,
) -> TutorialRunner:
    return build_command_runner(
        namespace=namespace,
        state_root=state_root,
        configured_tutorial_paths=configured_tutorial_paths(),
        command_tutorial_paths=command_tutorial_paths,
        shell_runner=shell_runner,
        editor_runner=editor_runner,
        question_runner=question_runner_override or question_runner,
        allow_shell=allow_shell,
        command_allow_shell=command_allow_shell,
        require_paths=require_paths,
    )
@

Completion callbacks are small, but they share the same configuration context
as the commands themselves.  Defining them here keeps the command signatures
compact without hiding where their data comes from.

<<define completion callbacks>>=
def run_tutorial_id_completion(ctx, incomplete: str) -> list[str]:
    command_paths = tuple(ctx.params.get("tutorial_path") or ())
    return suggest_run_tutorial_ids(
        configured_tutorial_paths(),
        command_paths,
        incomplete,
    )


def review_tutorial_id_completion(incomplete: str) -> list[str]:
    return suggest_review_tutorial_ids(
        namespace=namespace,
        state_root=state_root,
        incomplete=incomplete,
    )


def review_run_id_completion(ctx, incomplete: str) -> list[str]:
    tutorial_id = ctx.params.get("tutorial_id")
    if not isinstance(tutorial_id, str):
        return []
    return suggest_review_run_ids(
        tutorial_id,
        namespace=namespace,
        state_root=state_root,
        incomplete=incomplete,
    )
@

The list command is the smallest consumer of the shared runner: it only needs
the loaded catalog and saved progress.  That makes it a good first command to
register before the longer run and review flows.

<<register list command>>=
@application.command("list")
def list_command(
    tutorial_path: Annotated[
        list[Path] | None,
        typer.Option(
            "--tutorial-path",
            help=(
                "Path to a tutorial Markdown file or directory. "
                "Repeat to add more paths."
            ),
        ),
    ] = None,
) -> None:
    """List the loaded tutorials and their saved progress."""

    console = Console()
    try:
        tutorial_runner = runner(
            command_tutorial_paths=tuple(tutorial_path or ()),
            require_paths=True,
        )
    except (RuntimeError, ValueError) as error:
        typer.echo(str(error), err=True)
        raise typer.Exit(code=1)

    render_tutorial_list(console, tutorial_runner.list_tutorials())
@

The run command owns the most interactive path, so it only keeps the actual
prompt primitives local.  Step presentation and question-step dispatch now come
from shared helpers, which makes the contrast with argparse honest: the two
front ends differ in prompting surface and exit handling, not in tutorial-flow
policy.

<<register run command>>=
@application.command("run")
def run_command(
    tutorial_id: str = typer.Argument(
        ...,
        autocompletion=run_tutorial_id_completion,
    ),
    tutorial_path: Annotated[
        list[Path] | None,
        typer.Option(
            "--tutorial-path",
            help=(
                "Path to a tutorial Markdown file or directory. "
                "Repeat to add more paths."
            ),
        ),
    ] = None,
    restart: Annotated[
        bool,
        typer.Option(
            "--restart",
            help="Start a fresh run instead of resuming saved progress.",
        ),
    ] = False,
    allow_shell_flag: Annotated[
        bool,
        typer.Option(
            "--allow-shell",
            help=(
                "Trust tutorial-authored shell code in pre_command, "
                "check_command, and post_command for this run."
            ),
        ),
    ] = False,
) -> None:
    """Run or resume one tutorial."""

    console = Console()

    def prompt_for_input(prompt: str) -> str:
        return typer.prompt(prompt)

    def prompt_for_editor_start(prompt: str) -> str:
        return typer.prompt(prompt, default="", show_default=False)

    def before_step(tutorial, step_index, step, run) -> None:
        render_step_for_run(
            console=console,
            tutorial=tutorial,
            step_index=step_index,
            step=step,
            run=run,
            prompt_for_editor_start=prompt_for_editor_start,
        )

    command_question_runner = make_question_step_runner(
        console=console,
        prompt_for_input=prompt_for_input,
        question_runner=question_runner,
    )

    try:
        tutorial_runner = runner(
            command_tutorial_paths=tuple(tutorial_path or ()),
            command_allow_shell=allow_shell_flag,
            require_paths=True,
            question_runner_override=command_question_runner,
        )
        result = run_tutorial_with_menu(
            tutorial_runner,
            tutorial_id,
            restart=restart,
            before_step=before_step,
            console=console,
            prompt_for_input=prompt_for_input,
        )
    except KeyError as error:
        raise typer.BadParameter(str(error), param_hint="tutorial_id")
    except (RuntimeError, ValueError) as error:
        typer.echo(str(error), err=True)
        raise typer.Exit(code=1)

    if result.blocked_step is not None:
        raise typer.Exit(code=1)

    emit_run_summary(result)
@

Review is the third and final command because it reuses the same runner wiring
without needing the interactive prompting machinery from [[run]].  Ending the
factory with this command lets the reader contrast the lighter review flow with
the richer run path immediately above it.

<<register review command>>=
@application.command("review")
def review_command(
    tutorial_id: str = typer.Argument(
        ...,
        autocompletion=review_tutorial_id_completion,
    ),
    step: Annotated[
        int | None,
        typer.Option(
            "--step",
            min=1,
            help="Review only the latest transcript for one step.",
        ),
    ] = None,
    run_id: str | None = typer.Option(
        None,
        "--run-id",
        help="Review a specific saved run instead of the latest one.",
        autocompletion=review_run_id_completion,
    ),
) -> None:
    """Review saved transcripts for one tutorial."""

    console = Console()
    try:
        tutorial_runner = runner()
        tutorial, run, transcripts = tutorial_runner.review(
            tutorial_id,
            step_number=step,
            run_id=run_id,
        )
    except (KeyError, IndexError, ValueError) as error:
        typer.echo(str(error), err=True)
        raise typer.Exit(code=1)

    render_review_output(
        console,
        tutorial.title,
        run.run_id,
        run.workspace,
        transcripts,
    )
